o	Silat is a collective term for a class of indigenous martial arts originating from the Nusantara Archipelago region, which includes modern-day Malaysia, Indonesia, Brunei, and parts of the Philippines and Thailand. This martial art form is categorized into three main types: Silat Olahraga (Sport Silat), Silat Tari (Dance Silat), and Seni Silat (Martial Arts Silat). In recent years, Silat has gained international recognition both as a sport and as a cultural heritage. It is practiced all around the world and is part of many international martial arts competitions. UNESCO recognised Silat as an Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity in 2019, highlighting its mechanism which is defensive close combat battle.

Women in Management (WIM) Society aims to educate, empower, and up-skill UNSW students, staff and broader community, specifically, women/female-identifying individuals in pursuing more decision-making and management roles within and beyond the workplace/industry- a space where women are severely underrepresented. At our core, we seek to serve as a social and professional support network for UNSW women and advocate for a level playing field for all within and beyond the workplace.

Women in Politics aims to empower people from marginalised backgrounds in public decision making sectors including politics, government, NGOs, IGOs, media, economy, etc. We hold educational and networking events that allow students interested in these spaces to learn more about them, and get involved.

The Women in Science Society is a club that advocates for the promotion of equal representation in science through a variety of social and professional events. We're all gender inclusive, and will be posting regular events and opportunities for our members to participate in. We run a Peer Mentor Program in Term 2 and 3 that helps empower STEMM students via learning from strong female mentors but are always open to supporting students in need of mentoring from all faculties.

Founded in 2016, UNSW Women In Technology (WIT) is a network of 1000+ students with similar interests and goals surrounding STEM, and has grown into a platform to support and encourage diversity within the technology industry. WIT is proud of its innovative and positive environment, whereby long term connections and friendships are made, helping to play a part in removing the gender imbalance that exists in the sector.

Join the UNSW Yoga Club, a wellness-focused community dedicated to promoting health and mindfulness among students. We offer regular yoga sessions, meditation practices, and workshops suitable for all levels.

Young Entrepreneurs Program (YEP!) is an entrepreneurial education program for high school students hosted at University campuses. We create an 8-week incubator organized by university students to help build high school students’ confidence, and capabilities.
Youth Music Mission (YMM) is a Christian faith based club caters for all UNSW Students.
